        <body>
            <div type="bibliography" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#Evangelidis1952"/>, <citedRange>306 no 24</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/> <citedRange>15.396</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Eidinow2007"/>, <citedRange>84 no 5</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneLhôte"/>  <citedRange>40</citedRange></bibl>); <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/> <citedRange>19A</citedRange></bibl> (<bibl><ptr target="#CIOD"/> <citedRange>19A</citedRange></bibl>[last consulted 10/07/2026]).</p>
                <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2007d"/>, <citedRange>303 n. 66</citedRange></bibl></p>
                 </div>
<div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
    <ab>
        <lb n="1"/>βέλτιον πιπασ<lb n="2" break="no"/>κόμενωι γυναῖκα;
          </ab>
</div>
            <div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
                <app loc="ll. 1-2">
                <note>Evangelidis proposed the following reading, which is also adopted in <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneLhôte"/></bibl>: <foreign xml:lang="grc">βέλτιον ΠΙΠΑΥ..ΓΑΝ.. | .κομένωι γυναῖκα | πράσσοιμι</foreign>. As noted by the editors of <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/></bibl>, however, the third line actually belongs to inscription 20A.</note></app>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
     <p>Better for him to purchase a woman?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="es">
        <p>¿Mejor para él comprar una mujer?</p>
        </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
<p>On the productive lexical family of <foreign xml:lang="grc">πάομαι</foreign> (Att.-Ion. <foreign xml:lang="grc">κτάομαι</foreign>) in the oracular tablets, see <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2007"/>, <citedRange>302-304</citedRange></bibl> and <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2024"/>, <citedRange>§ 4.1</citedRange></bibl>. Pace <bibl><ptr target="#CIOD"/></bibl>, the reference to a female slave does not necessarily imply a prospective marriage. Likewise, the proposal that this is the same consultant as in <foreign xml:lang="la">I. Dodone Online</foreign> <ref target="i-dodone-online-5a">22A</ref> remains speculative.</p>
                
                <p n="Ithaca results">In the geographical output, Ithaca assigns the highest probability to Epirus (95.34%), while the chronological distribution peaks at 400-390 BC (17.46%). See <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline19A_2026_06_28.html">Ithaca results</ref> and <ref target="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IDodone/IDodoneOnline/refs/heads/main/ithaca-results/IDodoneOnline19A.md">metadata</ref>, and a snapshot of the <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline19A_geographical-attribution_2026_06.jpg">geographical attribution</ref>.</p>
                </div>
        </body>
